          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Russian base in Sudan</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/lavrov-sharif-handshake-moscow-press-conference.png" alt="Russian Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov and his Sudanese counterpart Ali Yusuf al-Sharif shake hands during a press conference in Moscow" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">Russian Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov and his Sudanese counterpart Ali Yusuf al-Sharif shake hands during a press conference in Moscow. Credits: Maxim Shemetov/ AFP
 </p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
         
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">After Sudan confirmed plans for a Red Sea military port, Russia is set to <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-19-02-2025-h1-1-establish-its-first-naval-base-in-africa?source=website" target="_blank">establish its first naval base in Africa</a>. The agreement, signed in 2020, allows Russia to station up to four navy ships, including nuclear-powered vessels, for 25 years. Russia would join the US and China in the region that connects the Suez Canal to the Indian Ocean.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        The Red Sea, one of the world’s most strategically important waterways, connects the Suez Canal to the Indian Ocean and facilitates about 12% of global trade. The base is also a silver lining amid the Syria situation, which threatens Russia’s Tartus base. The initial agreement stated that the bases were for logistical purposes and were “defensive and not aimed against other countries.”
       </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Sudan’s humanitarian crisis worsens, with displacement and famine fears rising. Russia backed Sudan at the UN Security Council, vetoing a ceasefire. Since Wagner leader Yevgeny Prigozhin’s death, the Kremlin has deepened ties with Sudan’s military. As the Sudanese army gains ground, Russia solidifies its influence, having previously played both sides in the conflict.
</p>
        </mj-text>
