          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">State Department stirs the pot</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;"><strong>Summary: The US State Department has removed a key phrase from its website on the subject of Taiwan, irritating China.</strong></p>

          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">The US has removed the key phrase “<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-19-02-2025-h3-3-we-do-not-support-taiwan-independence?source=website" target="_blank">we do not support Taiwan independence</a>” from its State Department website as part of a routine update. This sparked a sharp backlash from China. Beijing called the move a "serious regression" and warned of further damage to US-China relations, which are already low. China’s ruling Communist Party regards the self-governing democracy as its territory.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Trump's return to the White House and his hawkish foreign policy team, including Secretary of State Marco Rubio, have heightened tensions. Taiwan welcomed the change and sees it as a sign of growing US support. The US maintains its "one China policy" but opposes unilateral changes to the status quo. A dozen of smaller countries recognize Taiwan officially.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">China, under Xi Jinping, continues to try to isolate Taiwan, while the US and other “allies” naval activity in the Taiwan Strait has further escalated tensions. Washington also said it will continue to support Taiwan’s meaningful participation in international organizations. Last week, two US Navy ships sailed through the Taiwan Strait, drawing an angry response from China’s military.</p>
        </mj-text>
