          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
            <strong>🇨🇷 Costa Rica plans to accept a flight from the US carrying 200 migrants</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Costa Rica will temporarily host migrants deported from the US before they are <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-19-02-2025-br2-5-sent-back-to-their-home-countries?source=website" target="_blank">sent back to their home countries</a>. The first group of 200 migrants from Central Asia and India is set to arrive on Wednesday at a center near the Panama border, funded by the US and supervised by the International Organization for Migration (IOM). </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">As Trump’s administration increases mass deportations, India's cooperation in taking back undocumented migrants has led to backlash over images of deported Indians in handcuffs. Latin American countries are becoming crucial in Trump’s hardline immigration policies. Guatemala and Panama have also made similar agreements, with Panama already receiving 119 migrants from China, Pakistan, and Afghanistan.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
