          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">What is Navalny’s legacy?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/alexei-navalny-russian-opposition-leader.png" alt="Russian opposition leader Alexei Navalny" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">Russian opposition leader Alexei Navalny. Credits: Evgeny Feldman for Alexei Navalny’s campaign/ Handout/ Anadolu agency/ Getty Images</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">This week marked the first anniversary of the death of Russian critic <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="http://gs-19-02-2025-f1-6-aleksey-navalny?source=website" target="_blank">Aleksey Navalny</a>’s death. According to Russian data, the 47-year-old took a short walk at his Siberian penal colony, said he felt unwell, then collapsed and didn’t regain consciousness. The details around his death have come into question, whereas the Kremlin ruled it as a “combined disease with no criminal intent.”
</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">His legacy springs mixed reactions. Many view him as a symbol of courage and a fighter for democracy in Russia. He was the most prominent critic of Vladimir Putin; he exposed government corruption, mobilized mass protests, and inspired a generation of political activists. He survived poisoning and years in prison while remaining defiant, refusing exile and returning to Russia, knowing the risks.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Others do not have as rosy an image of him. While he changed his views on Ukraine later, he initially supported the Russian invasion of Ukraine. He said Crimea is not a sandwich to be passed back and forth. However, in one of his later court appearances in 2022, he stated, “I am against this war. I consider it immoral, fratricidal, and criminal.”</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Many Russians see him as an enemy of the state and paid by the West; however, he garnered favor among average Russians as weak. Some Russians who protested his detention were doing so for the first time. Regardless of which narrative is true, Alexei Navalny will remain known as one of the prominent figures of Russian resistance to Putin and the political system in Russia.</p>
        </mj-text>
